<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920115-0007</DOCNO><DOCID>920115-0007.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Rogers Corp.:   Firm Expects to Post Loss   Totaling $2.3 Million for '91</HL><DATE>01/15/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   ROG</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>ELECTRICAL COMPONENTS AND EQUIPMENT (ELQ)</IN><NS>EARNINGS PROJECTIONS (ERP)</NS><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Rogers Corp. said it expects to report an after-tax lossof $2.3 million for 1991, compared with a year-earlier lossof $2.5 million, due to slow sales and write-offs related tocost-cutting measures.   The Rogers, Conn., maker of electronic connectors andcomponents said its costcutting efforts will include a 3%decrease in salaried staff, product-line reductions and assetwrite-offs.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;The recession has severely affected sales, particularlyin the computer disk drive and automotive markets,&quot; Norman L.Greenman, the company's president, said in a release. He saidthat Rogers remains financially strong and that thewrite-offs and cost-cutting will &quot;accelerate the return toprofitability when the economy improves.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>